        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We estimated the SZ flux based on a simulated galaxy cluster merger using FLASH (an adaptive mesh refinement N--body-- hydrodynamical code) assuming $M1 = 2.1 x 10^{15}$~Msun, $M2 = 7 x 10^{14}$~Msun with an impact parameter of 150 kpc and a high relative velocity of 4800 km/sec. The absolute mass (and hence SZE flux) was not critical because later on, the simulated SZE signal is normalized using the Mustang and/or AMiBA results. 
For the line of sight projection, we did not assume that the main plane of the collision (the plane of the mass centers and velocity vectors) was in the plane of the sky, but rotated 30 Degrees out of it along an axis perpendicular to the line connecting the two dark matter centers. With this projection we can approximately reproduce the observed X-ray emission and SZ signal from this cluster. 
The masses, the impact parameter and large impact velocity were 
chosen to best reproduce the elongated X-ray feature of the main cluster emission and the morphology of the MUSTANG SZE image.


Requested sensitivity:

To simulate the likelihood of detection with Cycle 1 ALMA capability, we first smooth the sky model mentioned above to the same resolution of Mustang results and normalize the peak flux to the SE peak see in left panel of Figure 2. 
We then pass the normalized sky model (pixel resolution = 0.8") to CASA simulator using the most compact configuration ('alma.cycle2.1.cfg'), which for the target's Declination gives a resolution of $4"\times8"$. 
The noise-free map is shown in the left panel of Figure 3. The primary and secondary peaks are expected to have 76 and 35 uJy/bm, 
respectively. Based on this estimation, we request the 12m array to have a sensitivity of 7~uJy/bm, which corresponds to roughly 4 hours of on-source exposure. 


Imaging requirements:

In this proposal we do not require imaging structures larger than 25". Only 12m array is required.
</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
